04558nam a22006615i 9780674029521DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221999mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740295217 a10.4159/97806740295212doi  a(DE-B1597)574374  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aDS109.94 ǂb C49 1999eb 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a323.1/1927405694421 aCheshin, Amir, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSeparate and Unequal :bThe Inside Story of Israeli Rule in East Jerusalem /cAvi Melamed, Amir Cheshin, Bill Hutman. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- t1 The Vision and the Reality -- t2 Mr. Jerusalem -- t3 When Giants Sleep -- t4 A Question of Trust -- t5 Mr. Arafat, Can You Lend Me A Hand? -- t6 The Eagle Has Landed -- t7 The Forgotten Ones -- t8 Security Breach -- t9 Damage Control -- t10 A First Friendship -- t11 No Judenrein in Jerusalem -- t12 A Path to Peace Not Taken -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tMaps -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis vivid behind-the-scenes account of Israeli rule in Jerusalem details for the first time the Jewish state's attempt to lay claim to all of Jerusalem, even when that meant implementing harsh policies toward the city's Arab population. The authors, Jerusalemites from the spheres of politics, journalism, and the military, have themselves been players in the drama that has unfolded in east Jerusalem in recent years and appears now to be at a climax. They have also had access to a wide range of official documents that reveal the making and implementation of Israeli policy toward Jerusalem. Their book discloses the details of Israel's discriminatory policies toward Jerusalem Arabs and shows how Israeli leaders mishandled everything from security and housing to schools and sanitation services, to the detriment of not only the Palestinian residents but also Israel's own agenda. Separate and Unequal is a history of lost opportunities to unite the peoples of Jerusalem. A central focus of the book is Teddy Kollek, the city's outspoken mayor for nearly three decades, whose failures have gone largely unreported until now. But Kollek is only one character in a cast that includes prime ministers, generals, terrorists, European and American leaders, Arab shopkeepers, Israeli policemen, and Palestinian schoolchildren. The story the authors tell is as dramatic and poignant as the mosaic of religious and ethnic groups that call Jerusalem home. And coming at a time of renewed crisis, it offers a startling perspective on past mistakes that can point the way toward more equitable treatment of all Jerusalemites.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aPalestinian ArabsxGovernment policyxJerusalem. 0aPalestinian ArabsxGovernment policyzJerusalem. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh1 aHutman, Bill, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMelamed, Avi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674029521423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674029521/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK